Czech discovery: a substance that also works in ‘steel’ HIV viruses
The team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds to prevent the spread of HIV viruses in the organism.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also works in the viruses that are already resistant to drugs.
This fact predominates against the disadvantage that the connection to common virus variants does not work as strongly as one of the already existing medicines.
The disease AIDS cannot be cured yet.
However, the patient can prolong his life and prevent the proliferation of HIV viruses in the body.
However, their intake is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of virus proliferation results in the development of resistance viruses that are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences CR, from the VSCHT (Chemical-Technological University) Prague and from the University of Heidelberg opens the way to dealing with virus resistance.
They have shown that the substances known as metalocarborane act on the protein responsible for increasing the HIV virus.
Metalocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block virus proliferation in ways other than all medicines used today, so they can overcome the resistance problem.
In their work, the scientists have developed new “improved” connections prepared on the basis of the knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding on the virus protein.
Metalocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-faceted cages consisting of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms, coupled by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
Hectic and persistent virus
HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without the HIV virus division caused by the HIV protease, no mature infection virus particles would arise.
When we turn off the HIV protease, we also turn off the virus propagation in the patient's body, the scientists explain in the press report published by the Institute for Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences CR.
In the work published in the scientific journal Journal of Medical Chemistry, the scientists describe whole series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are coupled by a short organic chain, which is then systematically changed.
A little weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against the HIV protease is tested in the test tube, including against their persistent (resistant) variants obtained from HIV infected patients.
The effect of metalocarborane on the usual enzyme variant is not as strong as on the clinically used medicinal products but does not lose its effect on the resistance variants against which the medicines used are often effective.
The unique mechanism of action, as well as its further properties, such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical designs, makes the metalocarborans interesting for further research aimed at the development of effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlina Rezacova, Head of the Laboratory for Structural Biology of the Institutes of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
