Can Islam be French?
Pluralism and pragmatism in a secular state.
At a time when Swiss voters voted for a construction ban on minarette and the concern about the alleged Islamization of Europe is widespread, John Bowen, an American academic, wrote a well-founded and well-considered report on whether Muslims can be integrated into one of Europe's most secularized societies — and integrated.
Some readers will read this new book out of admiration for the author's last work: "Why the French don't love headscarves" (original title: "Why the French Don't Like Headscarves") (2006), an elegant and densely argumentative study of a dispute that divided the country over a decade and a half, and whose effects are still perceived today.
Bowen's newest book offers a wider and bolder spectrum.
As a good anthropologist, he wants to know not only what politicians and the media say about Islam in France, but what really happens in the area.
He has spent months in mosques, schools and institutes, which now offer 5 to 6 million Muslims in France, as Bowen calls it "Islamic spaces".
He is a good listener, he gives up debates between teachers and students on the questions they most worry about.
Should a Muslim marry in a mosque or a town hall (or both)?
Should young Muslims be taught about the evolution and rights of homosexuals?
Can a Muslim woman marry a non-Muslim man?
Is it possible for a Muslim to use a sentence-oriented banking system to obtain a mortgage?
It is these seemingly profanity issues, he claims, which make up everyday life, quite unlike the political dramas that the media employ.
The author recognizes a new generation of imams, teachers and intellectuals, none of them with a well-known name, possibly with the exception of Tarik Ramadan, an Arabic-Muslim scholar and academic born in Switzerland.
This new generation is trying to open up the debate on how it is possible to be a good Muslim on the one hand and a good citizen in a modern secular society on the other.
They don't have all the arguments on their side.
The conservatives are suspicious of the idea of a French or European Islam.
The thinkers and activists who interviewed Bowen are mostly disunited with their salafi counterparts – the proconsuls of purist Sunni Islam, which is associated with Saudi Arabia – which nowadays shows a small but influential presence among the Muslims of Europe.
Bowen believes that Muslim values and French secularism could be compatible.
But an agreement requires giving and taking on both sides.
He questions the extent to which French political decision-makers (and the intellectual elite, who so passionately guard the separation of Church and State) really feel committed to pluralism.
He suggests that Muslims may have experienced a more harsh treatment than Catholics, Protestants and Jews who had to make their historical compromise with secular republicanism.
He is more aware of a "strengthening of the value screws" than of growing pragmatism.
Can Islam be French? After reading this book, you tend to say "Yes, but not yet".
