Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The two meters long and 1,50 meters large animal ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated skull with sharp, bent teeth, short arms with sickle collars and a long tail.
If the species had lived a few million years later, it would be nothing special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body characteristics, reports Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas in Austin and colleagues in Science magazine of Thursday.
The animal lived around 215 million years ago in today's New Mexico, which was located at the equator in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangäa.
Tawa opens a new window for the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
