Support for braking maneuvers in critical situations is now mandatory
As in the case of the ABS anti-blocking braking system and as is the case with the ESP stability control, the auxiliary systems for braking in emergency situations must become a mandatory equipment in the European cars.
In fact, they are already mandatory for all newly approved passenger cars and light small transporters, for the remaining vehicles, a vehicle period has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The action decided by the European Union aims to improve the protection of pedestrians, but it can also help to prevent many collisions due to their working methods.
The task of the emergency brake assistant is to exert more pressure on the brakes in the event of a critical braking maneuver, which the system detects on the brake pedal using the brake strength operated by the driver.
However, this system does not exert this pressure until the end.
According to a test commissioned by the component manufacturer for the Bosch vehicles, one third of the drivers involved in an accident did not come up before the collision to hit the brake pedal and half of them had not stopped with full force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The brake aid, on the other hand, intervenes with maximum force in the brake system, thereby reducing the brake time and thus also the brake distance that a car moves back during the brake procedure.
According to an EU study, up to 1,100 fatal accidents involving pedestrians could be prevented every year if all cars were equipped with this type of emergency brake assistant.
There would be even fewer accidents - it is estimated that every 4th accident could be prevented with personal injury - as soon as the so-called intelligent emergency braking systems become popular.
Then the vehicle is equipped with a system that detects obstacles (by radar or camera) and warns the driver, while at the same time it exerts a slight pressure on the brakes.
If the driver reacts then the system helps him to increase the pressure on the brake pedal if necessary.
If the driver does not respond to the warning and even if the collision is unavoidable, the brake assistant will exert maximum pressure on the brakes to keep the damage as low as possible in this way.
