Every day thousands of vehicles engaged in an accident are dragged into the workshops, where an assessor has to assess the damage caused and the cost of repair.
No one accident is the same and the calculation of the costs for the parts and hours of work can be a lengthy and complicated task.
The calculation of repair costs of between 20,000 and 30,000 euros per hand, including parts and hours of work, may take up to two or three hours.
On the other hand, with the support of the latest computer tools it is a question of minutes
This is why almost 100% of the experts use this type of system.
The service and application providers for the assessment of accidents and repairs collect the information they receive from manufacturers in order to process them afterwards and to offer them to their customers in the form of a useful program.
In Spain, Audatex, part of the US group Solera, is the market leader; 80% of all opinions are produced with their products.
The other two companies competing in the tool market for assessment and preparation of a report are GtMotive and Eurotax.
Working with the data that the manufacturers provide is anything but simple.
According to Eduardo Velázquez, sales manager of Audatex, 63 manufacturers and importers are working together, each of them providing the information in a different format.
Moreover, the amount of data to be processed is increasing to the point that even more versions, variants and motorizations have been on the market over the last five years than in the last fifteen years.
As soon as a new car comes onto the market, the work begins for the companies.
It is a laborious task, because each of the thousands of vehicle parts has to be catagolised and its price entered.
In addition, every model creates an "intelligent" graphics image on which you can "click" different parts of the vehicle.
If this is a much-sold model, the work can be completed in a week if the procedure goes forward quickly.
If this is a less common car, it can take up to three or four months. At present Audatex has 99.2% of the cars sold in Spain have complete information.
Among the more exclusive models, they have information about Porsche models, but they do not have Ferrari or Lamborghini.
With regard to the road-going vehicle park, it is more than 99%.
For the purpose of carrying out documentation and the production of databases, Audatex has eight centres distributed worldwide (Spain, France, Germany, the USA, Brazil, Mexico, China and Japan) and each of them has specialised in certain brands.
The national headquarters is located in Alcobendas (Madrid).
More than a hundred technicians (usually mechanics) simultaneously work there with three computer screens.
Audatex invests 90 million euros each year in the preparation of these databases.
Each month they collect 2.5 million data and their customers receive the updates every second day.
The development of this huge flow of information enables companies to use them in different ways and thus offer different products.
The most common use is the use for repairs and repairs, but depending on the country, there are also tools for managing scrap parts or for calculating the fault or residual value of a car.
The only company that informs about the value of used cars in Spain is Eurotax.
Audatex does not offer this offer in Spain, but in the United States.
When reviewing the products offered by Audatex, you can easily get an overview of the type of support it provides to industry experts.
This company offers ten different tools, with the star of AudaPlus products, a standard solution to assess accidents for the experts.
It includes vehicles, motorcycles as well as light and heavy industrial vehicles.
In addition to the costs for the parts, it includes the repair times estimated by the manufacturer or the painting prices.
This tool is paid depending on the purpose of use, i.e. for each opinion.
It will be most expensive for customers who rarely use it for a maximum of ten times a month, namely 5,75 Euros per month.
On the other hand, every insurance company that produces thousands of reviews negotiates the price with Audatex.
With other products, such as AudaVIN, you can fully identify a vehicle and the equipment with which it ran from the assembly belt using the chassis number alone.
AudaGlass deals with the vehicle discs, and AudaSupastas is an open-ended service on the Internet for vehicles that have been declared total damage.
Their statistical service is very useful in identifying trends, conducting geodemographic analyses or for obtaining information on the variations by brand and model.
For example, one can look at how many models of a particular car brand had to be in the workshop because of the pins or how many of them were involved in a serious accident during a certain period of time.
Gt motifs are the only Spanish company dedicated to the development of this type of computer tools.
It distributes among other Gt Estimates, which is also intended for experts and provides in the same way digital images, access to parts or prices and official working hours of the manufacturer.
Gt Motive is a company of the Group of Ones, founded in 1971 as a provider of services and solutions for the assessment of damage, loss or maintenance of vehicles.
The GT leader for advice is a reference product on the market.
They work with 24,000 users in workshops, 3,100 experts and 53 insurance companies.
Their volume of business has increased by 20% per year over the last three years and in 2008 sales amounted to EUR 10.8 million.
At the beginning of last year, they began to go to the international market with the opening of an office in Paris.
Audatex, on the other hand, was founded in Germany in 1966 and established in Spain in 1979.
According to the company's sources, 62% of its business in Europe and the rest of the world is carried out, and the remaining 38% in North and South America, with 900 insurance companies and 33,000 workshops, 3,000 of them in Spain.
The total turnover in the world of the group Solera (Audatex, Sidex, Informex ABZ, Hollander and IMS) amounts to 557 million dollars, 3.35 more than in 2008.
In this country, the company has revenue of 19.1 million euros, 7.2% more than in the previous year.
In 2005, the Group of Solera was worth $1 billion on the stock exchange and today their shares are traded at a value of 2.4 billion dollars.
Since 2007, they have been part of the Standard & Poor's Reference Index on the New York Stock Exchange.
